<DOC><DOCNO> AP900926-0037 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-09-26-90 0158EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-Bush-UN     09-26 0334</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bush-UN,300</SECOND><HEAD>Bush Schedules 20 Sessions With Foreign Leaders in New York</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush will hold one-on-one talks with20 foreign leaders during his three-day stay in New York over theweekend before addressing the United Nations General Assembly.   Among the leaders he will confer with are British Prime MinisterMargaret Thatcher, Japanese Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu, MexicanPresident Carlos Salinas de Gortari and Czech President VaclavHavel, as well as Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.   Most of the meetings will be held at Bush's suite at the WaldorfAstoria Hotel.   Here is the president's preliminary schedule:</TEXT><BYLINE>SATURDAY</BYLINE><TEXT>   Meetings with:   -President Cesar Gaviria of Colombia.   -Prime Minister Salim Al-Huss of Lebanon.   -President Violeta Chamorro of Nicaragua.   -Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki of Poland.   -Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu of Japan.</TEXT><BYLINE>SUNDAY</BYLINE><TEXT>   Bush first attends a reception at the U.N. with heads of state,and the opening ceremony for the Children's Summit. Afterwards hemeets with:   -NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner.   -President Alfredo Cristiani of El Salvador.   -President Carlos Salinas de Gortari of Mexico.   -Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez of Spain.   -President Hussain Mohammad Ershad of Bangladesh.   -President Fernando Collor de Mello of Brazil.   -President Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela.   -President Vaclav Havel of Czechoslovakia.   -Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of the United Kingdom.   Bush and Thatcher will dine together.</TEXT><BYLINE>MONDAY</BYLINE><TEXT>   Meetings with:   -President Carlos Menem of Argentina.   -President Luis Alberto Lacalle of Uruguay.   -Organization of African Unity Chairman Yowery Museveni ofUganda.   Bush will also have coffee with African heads of state beforedeparting for the United Nations. There he will meet with:   -U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar.   -U.N. General Assembly President Guido de Marco of Malta.   After his address to the General Assembly, Bush will return tothe Waldorf Astoria and meet with:   -Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.   Before returning to Washington, Bush will also speak at theministerial meeting of the Conference on Security and Cooperationin Europe, a 35-nation group that includes the United States andCanada.</TEXT></DOC>